From : {bold}Paul Qureshi{nobold} <paul.qureshi@btinternet.com>
{pp}
Hi guys.
{pp}
Well, I thought that maybe it was time to think about why I still love
my Amiga, and hopefully shine a little light for a few people.
{pp}
Lets start with Intuition, the Amiga's GUI. Can anyone honestly say they
have found a faster, easier system? When I say fast, I mean in the sense
that I can access everything I want quickly, and don't have to spend
time looking for it. When I say easier, I mean it's simpler to use and
less hassle, although perhaps a little more work for beginners. Okay,
these days you need a few patches and MUI, but essentially Intuition has
got all the basic principals right. Just look at Opus, it couldn't work
on any other windowing system.
{pp}
Next, some of the Amiga's special features. You may think that the
custom hardware is next to useless now, with everyone using graphics
cards, sound cards, I/O cards etc. Well, think again. I wouldn't write
off AGA or Paula anyway, but just look at some of the other stuff in
your Amiga. The floppy drive interface, for example. It might be a bit
slow for HD disks, but at least your computer does freeze up when you
format a disk like Windows does. The CIA timers are something that
gerneric PC hardware can't compete with too. Ever noticed how a PC can't
even seem to play animations on the net at constant speed? What about
games, they are never running at constant speed and it gives many people
vertigo sickness. Well, the CIA timers provide extreemly accurate timing
for just such applications.
{pp}
Lets not forget the classics of the past either, which still run today
on Amiga hardware better than any emulation. Not just the games, but all
the serious software. Plus, the Amiga PD scene is still one of the best,
with some amazing shareware and freeware software available. Can you
name a better editor than GoldED? What about a better email client than
YAM?
{pp}
Sometimes, you have to use a PC, but it's not like many people enjoy
wrestling with Windows apps. What Amiga users have is something special,
something that is too good to let die.
{pp}
Regards,{p}
Paul Qureshi{p}
--{p}
